82. Is sb eo quem novissime viderat eret tertius, ‘and-it was the third day from the last which he had seen! He had died the day before, but he had not seen daylight since the day before that. Hence Pliny is able to make a sort of quibble on the common phrase ‘novissimus dies,’ which usually meant the day of a man’s death, but in this case must be applied to the day before death, as the day of death was no day at all, dies alibi, illie nox omnibus nigrior densiorque. ‘Erat’ is a conjectural insertion by Mommsen. lt makes the construction smoother, and might easily have dropped out after ‘viderat’
